I hope I don't come off harsh. I'm just weighing in.

This is such an absolute slog to read (maybe a little terse). I feel the writer's (H_D's?) powers of abstraction are vivid and film-like, but sorely dissonant from his vision when committed to writ. This reads like one of the narrated segments of a screenplay. Forget the setting, this entire passage is way too suburban and docile to make the reader care about even half of this character's monologue. What's more, there's tons of information here that's just noisy and disorienting, but the scene and monologue are tonally prim. I doubt there's a shred of foreshadowing or subplot material presented here.
My senses are sadly unengaged... what's a woman's warm fur smell like to our protagonist? Not an animal's, that's just the baseline – after shampooing, conditioning, working, etc., what's that going to smell like? Embellish.
Syntax and error-correction are solid and on-point here. Writefriend needs to hone in the immediate scope of his perspectives and scene transitions. Match up the tone of your monologues with your protagonist's present mood and situation – if he's distressed and anxious, his monologuing will reflect that; his thoughts, racing; his observations, jarring. He may miss finer details he wouldn't normally as the onset of panic or paranoia prevail over his usually cool demeanor.
Likewise, if he's just going with the motions, ensure the tone puts your reader equally at ease. It's like conducting a symphony: you're in command of your reader's mood. Orchestrate the sum of your scenes in accord with what your protagonist is experiencing.
